reviews.review_text: 9-15-87 Grate show. Grate C Miller remaster. I've been listening to these september 87 shows all week and they are very good.

Fun show 87 is one of the most underrated years.  The band had a cleaned, tightened, and expanded big sound.  More peaked out, high energy total  band jams.  I have heard other people say the drummers 'figured it out.' but it seemed like there was a particular groove that was in play post coma.

the hey pockey way> minglewood opener is very nice, as is the rest of the first set. A little technical difficulties of an otherwise strong Q janes. Row Jimmy makes a beautiful addition to the repotoire in this time period.  Music really gets out there with a powerful finish.

Set II
good solid well played 
post drumz
watchtower tease before a soulful extended Black Peter.

Pretty good This show gets off to a strong start with Brent really diggin in on Pockey. Row Jimmy is nice. Queen Jane is all screwed up. Ten Jed has Jerry's guitar breaking up and Healey pulling it out of the mix while he tries to fix it. 

2nd set rips

electronic mice/watch your speed My first MSG show.  I suppose this was true of pretty much anybody my age who hadn't been born into a situation featuring older deadhead brothers and distracted parents like my friend Drew was.  There was lots of hype for this one and a lot of anticipation.  The band was still riding a hot streak and the first third of the tour had been hot.  I was still buzzing from a Providence run that had a strong share of focused playing and 85-like surprise, crowd-pleasing cover song breakouts.  The Maryland setlists looked very fresh and energetic even from the paper they were printed on. Those of us pretending to give more of af about Fall Semester than Fall Tour were kicking themselves for missing that second set Cumberland opener and many of the big tunes (First two Providence pre-drums song selection isn't jammy enough to the pre-Touch deadhead)

So I've taken a very early fall break from classes for the week, I've got a spot at a small hostel in Soho and every night surrounded by German college students who are probably wondering why I seem to sweat the smell of chemicals when I roll in before they lock the door at 2:00.  I have tickets to the first two nights and GDTS gave me an extra for tonight that I hope to be able to trade for the very difficult Friday ticket.  Everyone thinks the Friday show is going to be the big show here on Tuesday so it's not even out there.  Well after I should be negotiating such things on the streets of NY, I have the misfortune to catch the gleaming eye of a NY scalper who is willing to take my extra plus (I think it might have been 20 or 30 dollars but that was worth more then...the street value of the Fri ticket was going for 90-100.) Needless to say, I got a (probably fake) ticket for tonight with a worse location than the one I traded.  Sigh.  I gave it away with the caveat.  Hope they made it.

So I was in what I think used to be called the "stadium" section, or at least was in the Boston Garden: the seats just behind and above the seats next to the ice.  Anyway, the sound sucked there.  I non-patiently waited it out for the first three songs but it was kind of like having the mono setting on your headphones accidentally with buzzing and not all the instruments in the mix.  Bobby said something.  I think I was on the move for Beer Barrell Polka, which is awesome and immediately while listening to this tape, I feel like I am transported back to a 73 NY show.  There is something wrong with Bob's rig certainly and possibly other things in the sound system and while these problems never totally go away in this show, they are most prominent in the first set.  The performances are solid especially the final two.

Second set is a classic New York Grateful Dead set through and through.  I don't recall the sound improving that much at the show but it does on the recording as does the band's overall confidence and focus.  They sound more settled in than they did in the first set and I can't blame them.  New York City at that time was truly 'too much of anything is just enough' and I'm sure they were exhausted with the thrill of it all. I know I was.  I had a feeling the second night was going to be the special night and I had no worries about Friday.  I knew that a deadhead is "someone who doesn't have a ticket and gets in free"
No St. Stephen Everyone thought they were goign to bust out St. Stephen after the 1983 MSG run of shows. Of course they didn't but it was a great time nonetheless.
